Hi,

**What did you do?**
We have an embedded c++ Python program that runs scripts in a clean Python environment by always creating a fresh environment with Py_Initialize and Py_Finalize. I tried adding some  processing with uiautomator2 but that causes the application to crash on the second run of the script. I print the errors, it shows something wrong with PIL._imaging.

**What did you expect to happen?**
The module should load properly after the Python state has been cleared and re-created.

**What actually happened?**
The module failed when import PIL.Image.

**What versions of Pillow and Python are you using?**
Pillow 7.1.2
Python 3.6.5 64x
Windows 10

Code to reproduce

```c
#include <iostream>
#include <Python.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
	Py_SetPythonHome((wchar_t*)L"D:\\Python\\Python36");
	Py_InitializeEx(0);
	if(!Py_IsInitialized()){
		cout << "Python initial failed" << endl;
		Py_Finalize();
	}
	
	PyObject* pModule;
	PyObject* pFunc = NULL;
	PyObject* pArg = NULL;

	PyRun_SimpleString("import sys");
	//PyRun_SimpleString("from PIL import Image");
	PyRun_SimpleString("sys.path.append('D:/Data/java/CppPython1')");
	PyRun_SimpleString("print(sys.path)");
	pModule=PyImport_ImportModule("PIL.Image");
	
	//pModule = PyImport_ImportModule("PIL");
	//pModule = PyImport_ImportModule("uiautomator2");
	//pModule = PyImport_Import(moduleName);
	if (!pModule) {
		cout << "import moudle failed"<<pModule << endl;
		PyErr_Print(); 
		return -1;
	}
	//pFunc = PyObject_GetAttrString(pModule, "connect");
	//if (!pFunc) {
	//	cout << "import module failed"  << endl;
	//	return -1;
	//}
	//PyObject_CallFunction(pFunc,"");
}
```

Output:

import module failed
```
